Hello again all,

One hypothesis that we describe in the paper is *why* thi=
s phenomenon occurs. We have a figure (14) and text describing our hypothes=
is in the paper, but an earlier draft had a figure dedicated just to this i=
ssue that we omitted for space. (though we hope to include it in the final =
version of the paper): 



The caption would have pointed out that, with a =
supervised model, when generating images that a DNN maximally believes are =
members of the class, the produced image (red triangle) will be placed far =
away from the decision boundary, and thus far away from exemplars of the cl=
ass, and therefore will likely be unrecognizable. With a generative encodin=
g, however, the red triangle is likely to be closer to class exemplars (tho=
ugh it is still an open question as to whether it would look natural/recogn=
izable, as the space within the manifold could still be large and consist o=
f many unrecognizable images). We plan to conduct experiments with generati=
ve DNNs in our GECCO submission. 
 
Interestingly, someone just pointed out=
 to me that Tinbergen showed that the same phenomenon occurs in natural ani=
mals! Here is a nice comic summarizing the fascinating data: 

https://imgu=
r.com/a/ibMUn <https://imgur.com/a/ibMUn>

According to the comic, Tinberge=
n called them =E2=80=9Csupernormal stimuli=E2=80=9D=E2=80=A6maybe we should=
 have done the same!


Best regards,
Jeff Clune

Assistant Professor, Compu=
ter Science
Director, Evolving Artificial Intelligence Lab <http://evolving=
ai.org/>
University of Wyoming
jeffclune@...
jeffclune.com

> On Dec 8=
, 2014, at 11:43 AM, Jeff Clune <jclune@...> wrote:
> 
> Hello all, 
=
> 
> I am pleased to announce a new paper called =E2=80=9CDeep Neural Netwo=
rks are Easily Fooled: High Confidence Predictions for Unrecognizable Image=
s.=E2=80=9D It was written by Anh Nguyen, Jason Yosinski, and myself. 
> 
>=
 The main point of the paper is that Deep Neural Networks see the world ver=
y differently than humans, often rating images that are completely unrecogn=
izable to us as natural objects (e.g. guitars, penguins) with near-certaint=
y. 
> 
> http://arxiv.org/abs/1412.1897 <http://arxiv.org/abs/1412.1897>
> =

> But probably of even more interest to those on this list is what happens=
 when you combine Deep Learning with evolution. Check out the amazing diver=
sity of CPPN images you get! I think people on this list will enjoy at leas=
t browsing those figures. Note that the evolution is driven by a new type o=
f evolutionary algorithm that Jean-Baptiste Mouret and I have invented call=
ed =E2=80=9Cmulti-dimensional archive of phenotypic elites=E2=80=9D (MAP-El=
ites). You can read more about that in this paper: http://arxiv.org/abs/140=
7.3501 <http://arxiv.org/abs/1407.3501>
> 
> As we mention in this new pape=
r, we are actively at work combining Deep Neural Networks with Evolution (s=
pecifically DNNs + MAP-Elites + CPPNs) to try to automatically create more =
open-ended evolution. The goal is to algorithmically automate the magic tha=
t happened on PicBreeder and EndlessForms.com <http://endlessforms.com/>. W=
e hope to have a paper on that finished in time to submit to GECCO. I will =
be excited to share our ideas and data with you once that is ready. 
> 
> C=
ongratulations to new Evolving AI Lab member Anh Nguyen on putting together=
 this paper. 
> 
> As always, please let us know if you have any questions.=
 
> 
> 
> 
> Best regards,
> Jeff Clune
> 
> Assistant Professor, Computer =
Science
> Director, Evolving Artificial Intelligence Lab <http://evolvingai=
.org/>
> University of Wyoming
> jeffclune@... <mailto:jeffclune@uwyo.=
edu>
> jeffclune.com
>
